# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lua
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua is a powerful, efficient, lightweight, embeddable scripting language.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] It supports procedural programming, object-oriented programming, functional programming, data-driven programming, and data description.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua combines simple procedural syntax with powerful data description constructs based on associative arrays and extensible semantics.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua is dynamically typed, runs by interpreting bytecode with a register-based virtual machine, and has automatic memory management with a generational garbage collection, making it ideal for configuration, scripting, and rapid prototyping.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua is implemented as a library, written in *clean C*, the common subset of standard C and C++.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The Lua distribution includes a host program called `lua`, which uses the Lua library to offer a complete, standalone Lua interpreter, for interactive or batch use.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua is intended to be used both as a powerful, lightweight, embeddable scripting language for any program that needs one, and as a powerful but lightweight and efficient stand-alone language.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] As an extension language, Lua has no notion of a "main" program: it works *embedded* in a host client, called the *embedding program* or simply the *host*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] (Frequently, this host is the stand-alone `lua` program.) The host program can invoke functions to execute a piece of Lua code, can write and read Lua variables, and can register C functions to be called by Lua code.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Through the use of C functions, Lua can be augmented to cope with a wide range of different domains, thus creating customized programming languages sharing a syntactical framework.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua is free software, and is provided as usual with no guarantees, as stated in its license.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The implementation described in this manual is available at Lua's official web site, `www.lua.org`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Like any other reference manual, this document is dry in places.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For a discussion of the decisions behind the design of Lua, see the technical papers available at Lua's web site.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For a detailed introduction to programming in Lua, see Roberto's book, *Programming in Lua*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This section describes the basic concepts of the language.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This means that variables do not have types; only values do.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] There are no type definitions in the language.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] All values in Lua are first-class values.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This means that all values can be stored in variables, passed as arguments to other functions, and returned as results.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] There are eight basic types in Lua: *nil*, *boolean*, *number*, *string*, *function*, *userdata*, *thread*, and *table*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The type *nil* has one single value, **nil**, whose main property is to be different from any other value; it often represents the absence of a useful value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The type *boolean* has two values, **false** and **true**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Both **nil** and **false** make a condition false; they are collectively called *false values*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Despite its name, **false** is frequently used as an alternative to **nil**, with the key difference that **false** behaves like a regular value in a table, while a **nil** in a table represents an absent key.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The type *number* represents both integer numbers and real (floating-point) numbers, using two subtypes: *integer* and *float*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Standard Lua uses 64-bit integers and double-precision (64-bit) floats, but you can also compile Lua so that it uses 32-bit integers and/or single-precision (32-bit) floats.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The option with 32 bits for both integers and floats is particularly attractive for small machines and embedded systems.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Unless stated otherwise, any overflow when manipulating integer values *wrap around*, according to the usual rules of two-complement arithmetic.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua has explicit rules about when each subtype is used, but it also converts between them automatically as needed (see §3.4.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Therefore, the programmer may choose to mostly ignore the difference between integers and floats or to assume complete control over the representation of each number.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The type *string* represents immutable sequences of bytes.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua is 8-bit clean: strings can contain any 8-bit value, including embedded zeros ('`\0`').
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua is also encoding-agnostic; it makes no assumptions about the contents of a string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The length of any string in Lua must fit in a Lua integer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua can call (and manipulate) functions written in Lua and functions written in C (see §3.4.10).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Both are represented by the type *function*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The type *userdata* is provided to allow arbitrary C data to be stored in Lua variables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A userdata value represents a block of raw memory.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] There are two kinds of userdata: *full userdata*, which is an object with a block of memory managed by Lua, and *light userdata*, which is simply a C pointer value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Userdata has no predefined operations in Lua, except assignment and identity test.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] By using *metatables*, the programmer can define operations for full userdata values (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Userdata values cannot be created or modified in Lua, only through the C API.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This guarantees the integrity of data owned by the host program and C libraries.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The type *thread* represents independent threads of execution and it is used to implement coroutines (see §2.6).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua threads are not related to operating-system threads.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua supports coroutines on all systems, even those that do not support threads natively.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The type *table* implements associative arrays, that is, arrays that can have as indices not only numbers, but any Lua value except **nil** and NaN.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] (*Not a Number* is a special floating-point value used by the IEEE 754 standard to represent undefined numerical results, such as `0/0`.) Tables can be *heterogeneous*; that is, they can contain values of all types (except **nil**).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Any key associated to the value **nil** is not considered part of the table.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Conversely, any key that is not part of a table has an associated value **nil**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Tables are the sole data-structuring mechanism in Lua; they can be used to represent ordinary arrays, lists, symbol tables, sets, records, graphs, trees, etc.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] To represent records, Lua uses the field name as an index.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The language supports this representation by providing `a.name` as syntactic sugar for `a["name"]`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] There are several convenient ways to create tables in Lua (see §3.4.9).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Like indices, the values of table fields can be of any type.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In particular, because functions are first-class values, table fields can contain functions.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Thus tables can also carry *methods* (see §3.4.11).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The indexing of tables follows the definition of raw equality in the language.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The expressions `a[i]` and `a[j]` denote the same table element if and only if `i` and `j` are raw equal (that is, equal without metamethods).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In particular, floats with integral values are equal to their respective integers (e.g., `1.0 == 1`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] To avoid ambiguities, any float used as a key that is equal to an integer is converted to that integer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For instance, if you write `a[2.0] = true`, the actual key inserted into the table will be the integer `2`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Tables, functions, threads, and (full) userdata values are *objects*: variables do not actually *contain* these values, only *references* to them.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Assignment, parameter passing, and function returns always manipulate references to such values; these operations do not imply any kind of copy.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The library function `type` returns a string describing the type of a given value (see `type`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] As we will discuss further in §3.2 and §3.3.3, any reference to a free name (that is, a name not bound to any declaration) `var` is syntactically translated to `_ENV.var`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Moreover, every chunk is compiled in the scope of an external local variable named `_ENV` (see §3.3.2), so `_ENV` itself is never a free name in a chunk.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Despite the existence of this external `_ENV` variable and the translation of free names, `_ENV` is a completely regular name.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In particular, you can define new variables and parameters with that name.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Each reference to a free name uses the `_ENV` that is visible at that point in the program, following the usual visibility rules of Lua (see §3.5).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Any table used as the value of `_ENV` is called an *environment*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua keeps a distinguished environment called the *global environment*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This value is kept at a special index in the C registry (see §4.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In Lua, the global variable `_G` is initialized with this same value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] When Lua loads a chunk, the default value for its `_ENV` variable is the global environment (see `load`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Therefore, by default, free names in Lua code refer to entries in the global environment and, therefore, they are also called *global variables*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Moreover, all standard libraries are loaded in the global environment and some functions there operate on that environment.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You can use `load` (or `loadfile`) to load a chunk with a different environment.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Several operations in Lua can *raise* an error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] An error interrupts the normal flow of the program, which can continue by *catching* the error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua code can explicitly raise an error by calling the `error` function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] To catch errors in Lua, you can do a *protected call*, using `pcall` (or `xpcall`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The function `pcall` calls a given function in *protected mode*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Any error while running the function stops its execution, and control returns immediately to `pcall`, which returns a status code.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Because Lua is an embedded extension language, Lua code starts running by a call from C code in the host program.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Whenever there is an error, an *error object* is propagated with information about the error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua itself only generates errors whose error object is a string, but programs can generate errors with any value as the error object.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] It is up to the Lua program or its host to handle such error objects.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For historical reasons, an error object is often called an *error message*, even though it does not have to be a string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] When you use `xpcall` (or `lua_pcall`, in C) you can give a *message handler* to be called in case of errors.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This function is called with the original error object and returns a new error object.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] It is called before the error unwinds the stack, so that it can gather more information about the error, for instance by inspecting the stack and creating a stack traceback.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This message handler is still protected by the protected call; so, an error inside the message handler will call the message handler again.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If this loop goes on for too long, Lua breaks it and returns an appropriate message.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The message handler is called only for regular runtime errors.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] It is not called for memory-allocation errors nor for errors while running finalizers or other message handlers.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua also offers a system of *warnings* (see `warn`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Unlike errors, warnings do not interfere in any way with program execution.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] They typically only generate a message to the user, although this behavior can be adapted from C (see `lua_setwarnf`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Every value in Lua can have a *metatable*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This *metatable* is an ordinary Lua table that defines the behavior of the original value under certain events.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You can change several aspects of the behavior of a value by setting specific fields in its metatable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For instance, when a non-numeric value is the operand of an addition, Lua checks for a function in the field `__add` of the value's metatable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If it finds one, Lua calls this function to perform the addition.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The key for each event in a metatable is a string with the event name prefixed by two underscores; the corresponding value is called a *metavalue*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For most events, the metavalue must be a function, which is then called a *metamethod*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In the previous example, the key is the string "`__add`" and the metamethod is the function that performs the addition.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Unless stated otherwise, a metamethod can in fact be any callable value, which is either a function or a value with a `__call` metamethod.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You can query the metatable of any value using the `getmetatable` function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua queries metamethods in metatables using a raw access (see `rawget`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You can replace the metatable of tables using the `setmetatable` function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You cannot change the metatable of other types from Lua code, except by using the debug library (§6.10).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Tables and full userdata have individual metatables, although multiple tables and userdata can share their metatables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Values of all other types share one single metatable per type; that is, there is one single metatable for all numbers, one for all strings, etc.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] By default, a value has no metatable, but the string library sets a metatable for the string type (see §6.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A detailed list of operations controlled by metatables is given next.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Each event is identified by its corresponding key.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] By convention, all metatable keys used by Lua are composed by two underscores followed by lowercase Latin letters.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If any operand for an addition is not a number, Lua will try to call a metamethod.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] It starts by checking the first operand (even if it is a number); if that operand does not define a metamethod for `__add`, then Lua will check the second operand.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If Lua can find a metamethod, it calls the metamethod with the two operands as arguments, and the result of the call (adjusted to one value) is the result of the operation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Otherwise, if no metamethod is found, Lua raises an error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Behavior similar to the addition operation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Behavior similar to the addition operation, except that Lua will try a metamethod if any operand is neither an integer nor a float coercible to an integer (see §3.4.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Behavior similar to the bitwise AND operation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] **`__bxor`:** the bitwise exclusive OR (binary `~`) operation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Behavior similar to the addition operation, except that Lua will try a metamethod if any operand is neither a string nor a number (which is always coercible to a string).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If the object is not a string, Lua will try its metamethod.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If there is a metamethod, Lua calls it with the object as argument, and the result of the call (always adjusted to one value) is the result of the operation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If there is no metamethod but the object is a table, then Lua uses the table length operation (see §3.4.7).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Behavior similar to the addition operation, except that Lua will try a metamethod only when the values being compared are either both tables or both full userdata and they are not primitively equal.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The result of the call is always converted to a boolean.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Behavior similar to the addition operation, except that Lua will try a metamethod only when the values being compared are neither both numbers nor both strings.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Moreover, the result of the call is always converted to a boolean.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Behavior similar to the less than operation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] **`__index`:** The indexing access operation `table[key]`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This event happens when `table` is not a table or when `key` is not present in `table`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The metavalue is looked up in the metatable of `table`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The metavalue for this event can be either a function, a table, or any value with an `__index` metavalue.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If it is a function, it is called with `table` and `key` as arguments, and the result of the call (adjusted to one value) is the result of the operation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Otherwise, the final result is the result of indexing this metavalue with `key`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This indexing is regular, not raw, and therefore can trigger another `__index` metavalue.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] **`__newindex`:** The indexing assignment `table[key] = value`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Like the index event, this event happens when `table` is not a table or when `key` is not present in `table`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Like with indexing, the metavalue for this event can be either a function, a table, or any value with an `__newindex` metavalue.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If it is a function, it is called with `table`, `key`, and `value` as arguments.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Otherwise, Lua repeats the indexing assignment over this metavalue with the same key and value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This assignment is regular, not raw, and therefore can trigger another `__newindex` metavalue.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Whenever a `__newindex` metavalue is invoked, Lua does not perform the primitive assignment.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If needed, the metamethod itself can call `rawset` to do the assignment.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This event happens when Lua tries to call a non-function value (that is, `func` is not a function).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If present, the metamethod is called with `func` as its first argument, followed by the arguments of the original call (`args`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] All results of the call are the results of the operation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This is the only metamethod that allows multiple results.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In addition to the previous list, the interpreter also respects the following keys in metatables: `__gc` (see §2.5.3), `__close` (see §3.3.8), `__mode` (see §2.5.4), and `__name`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For the unary operators (negation, length, and bitwise NOT), the metamethod is computed and called with a dummy second operand, equal to the first one.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This extra operand is only to simplify Lua's internals (by making these operators behave like a binary operation) and may be removed in future versions.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For most uses this extra operand is irrelevant.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Because metatables are regular tables, they can contain arbitrary fields, not only the event names defined above.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Some functions in the standard library (e.g., `tostring`) use other fields in metatables for their own purposes.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] It is a good practice to add all needed metamethods to a table before setting it as a metatable of some object.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In particular, the `__gc` metamethod works only when this order is followed (see §2.5.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] It is also a good practice to set the metatable of an object right after its creation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua performs automatic memory management.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This means that you do not have to worry about allocating memory for new objects or freeing it when the objects are no longer needed.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua manages memory automatically by running a *garbage collector* to collect all *dead* objects.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] All memory used by Lua is subject to automatic management: strings, tables, userdata, functions, threads, internal structures, etc.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] An object is considered *dead* as soon as the collector can be sure the object will not be accessed again in the normal execution of the program.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] ("Normal execution" here excludes finalizers, which can resurrect dead objects (see §2.5.3), and excludes also operations using the debug library.) Note that the time when the collector can be sure that an object is dead may not coincide with the programmer's expectations.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The only guarantees are that Lua will not collect an object that may still be accessed in the normal execution of the program, and it will eventually collect an object that is inaccessible from Lua.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] (Here, *inaccessible from Lua* means that neither a variable nor another live object refer to the object.) Because Lua has no knowledge about C code, it never collects objects accessible through the registry (see §4.3), which includes the global environment (see §2.2).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The garbage collector (GC) in Lua can work in two modes: incremental and generational.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The default GC mode with the default parameters are adequate for most uses.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] However, programs that waste a large proportion of their time allocating and freeing memory can benefit from other settings.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Keep in mind that the GC behavior is non-portable both across platforms and across different Lua releases; therefore, optimal settings are also non-portable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You can change the GC mode and parameters by calling `lua_gc` in C or `collectgarbage` in Lua.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You can also use these functions to control the collector directly (e.g., to stop and restart it).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In incremental mode, each GC cycle performs a mark-and-sweep collection in small steps interleaved with the program's execution.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In this mode, the collector uses three numbers to control its garbage-collection cycles: the *garbage-collector pause*, the *garbage-collector step multiplier*, and the *garbage-collector step size*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The garbage-collector pause controls how long the collector waits before starting a new cycle.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The collector starts a new cycle when the use of memory hits *n%* of the use after the previous collection.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Larger values make the collector less aggressive.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Values equal to or less than 100 mean the collector will not wait to start a new cycle.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A value of 200 means that the collector waits for the total memory in use to double before starting a new cycle.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The default value is 200; the maximum value is 1000.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The garbage-collector step multiplier controls the speed of the collector relative to memory allocation, that is, how many elements it marks or sweeps for each kilobyte of memory allocated.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Larger values make the collector more aggressive but also increase the size of each incremental step.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You should not use values less than 100, because they make the collector too slow and can result in the collector never finishing a cycle.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The default value is 100; the maximum value is 1000.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The garbage-collector step size controls the size of each incremental step, specifically how many bytes the interpreter allocates before performing a step.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This parameter is logarithmic: A value of *n* means the interpreter will allocate *2n* bytes between steps and perform equivalent work during the step.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A large value (e.g., 60) makes the collector a stop-the-world (non-incremental) collector.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The default value is 13, which means steps of approximately 8 Kbytes.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In generational mode, the collector does frequent *minor* collections, which traverses only objects recently created.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If after a minor collection the use of memory is still above a limit, the collector does a stop-the-world *major* collection, which traverses all objects.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The generational mode uses two parameters: the *minor multiplier* and the *the major multiplier*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The minor multiplier controls the frequency of minor collections.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For a minor multiplier *x*, a new minor collection will be done when memory grows *x%* larger than the memory in use after the previous major collection.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For instance, for a multiplier of 20, the collector will do a minor collection when the use of memory gets 20% larger than the use after the previous major collection.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The default value is 20; the maximum value is 200.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The major multiplier controls the frequency of major collections.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For a major multiplier *x*, a new major collection will be done when memory grows *x%* larger than the memory in use after the previous major collection.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For instance, for a multiplier of 100, the collector will do a major collection when the use of memory gets larger than twice the use after the previous collection.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You can set garbage-collector metamethods for tables and, using the C API, for full userdata (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] These metamethods, called *finalizers*, are called when the garbage collector detects that the corresponding table or userdata is dead.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Finalizers allow you to coordinate Lua's garbage collection with external resource management such as closing files, network or database connections, or freeing your own memory.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For an object (table or userdata) to be finalized when collected, you must *mark* it for finalization.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You mark an object for finalization when you set its metatable and the metatable has a `__gc` metamethod.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Note that if you set a metatable without a `__gc` field and later create that field in the metatable, the object will not be marked for finalization.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] When a marked object becomes dead, it is not collected immediately by the garbage collector.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] After the collection, Lua goes through that list.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] For each object in the list, it checks the object's `__gc` metamethod: If it is present, Lua calls it with the object as its single argument.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] At the end of each garbage-collection cycle, the finalizers are called in the reverse order that the objects were marked for finalization, among those collected in that cycle; that is, the first finalizer to be called is the one associated with the object marked last in the program.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The execution of each finalizer may occur at any point during the execution of the regular code.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Because the object being collected must still be used by the finalizer, that object (and other objects accessible only through it) must be *resurrected* by Lua.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Usually, this resurrection is transient, and the object memory is freed in the next garbage-collection cycle.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] However, if the finalizer stores the object in some global place (e.g., a global variable), then the resurrection is permanent.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Moreover, if the finalizer marks a finalizing object for finalization again, its finalizer will be called again in the next cycle where the object is dead.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In any case, the object memory is freed only in a GC cycle where the object is dead and not marked for finalization.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] When you close a state (see `lua_close`), Lua calls the finalizers of all objects marked for finalization, following the reverse order that they were marked.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If any finalizer marks objects for collection during that phase, these marks have no effect.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Finalizers cannot yield nor run the garbage collector.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Because they can run in unpredictable times, it is good practice to restrict each finalizer to the minimum necessary to properly release its associated resource.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Any error while running a finalizer generates a warning; the error is not propagated.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A *weak table* is a table whose elements are *weak references*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A weak reference is ignored by the garbage collector.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In other words, if the only references to an object are weak references, then the garbage collector will collect that object.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A weak table can have weak keys, weak values, or both.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A table with weak values allows the collection of its values, but prevents the collection of its keys.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A table with both weak keys and weak values allows the collection of both keys and values.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In any case, if either the key or the value is collected, the whole pair is removed from the table.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The weakness of a table is controlled by the `__mode` field of its metatable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This metavalue, if present, must be one of the following strings: "`k`", for a table with weak keys; "`v`", for a table with weak values; or "`kv`", for a table with both weak keys and values.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A table with weak keys and strong values is also called an *ephemeron table*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In an ephemeron table, a value is considered reachable only if its key is reachable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In particular, if the only reference to a key comes through its value, the pair is removed.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Any change in the weakness of a table may take effect only at the next collect cycle.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In particular, if you change the weakness to a stronger mode, Lua may still collect some items from that table before the change takes effect.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Only objects that have an explicit construction are removed from weak tables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Values, such as numbers and light C functions, are not subject to garbage collection, and therefore are not removed from weak tables (unless their associated values are collected).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Although strings are subject to garbage collection, they do not have an explicit construction and their equality is by value; they behave more like values than like objects.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Therefore, they are not removed from weak tables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Resurrected objects (that is, objects being finalized and objects accessible only through objects being finalized) have a special behavior in weak tables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] They are removed from weak values before running their finalizers, but are removed from weak keys only in the next collection after running their finalizers, when such objects are actually freed.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This behavior allows the finalizer to access properties associated with the object through weak tables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If a weak table is among the resurrected objects in a collection cycle, it may not be properly cleared until the next cycle.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua supports coroutines, also called *collaborative multithreading*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A coroutine in Lua represents an independent thread of execution.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Unlike threads in multithread systems, however, a coroutine only suspends its execution by explicitly calling a yield function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You create a coroutine by calling `coroutine.create`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Its sole argument is a function that is the main function of the coroutine.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The `create` function only creates a new coroutine and returns a handle to it (an object of type *thread*); it does not start the coroutine.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You execute a coroutine by calling `coroutine.resume`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] When you first call `coroutine.resume`, passing as its first argument a thread returned by `coroutine.create`, the coroutine starts its execution by calling its main function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Extra arguments passed to `coroutine.resume` are passed as arguments to that function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] After the coroutine starts running, it runs until it terminates or *yields*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A coroutine can terminate its execution in two ways: normally, when its main function returns (explicitly or implicitly, after the last instruction); and abnormally, if there is an unprotected error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In case of normal termination, `coroutine.resume` returns **true**, plus any values returned by the coroutine main function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In case of errors, `coroutine.resume` returns **false** plus the error object.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In this case, the coroutine does not unwind its stack, so that it is possible to inspect it after the error with the debug API.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A coroutine yields by calling `coroutine.yield`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] When a coroutine yields, the corresponding `coroutine.resume` returns immediately, even if the yield happens inside nested function calls (that is, not in the main function, but in a function directly or indirectly called by the main function).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In the case of a yield, `coroutine.resume` also returns **true**, plus any values passed to `coroutine.yield`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The next time you resume the same coroutine, it continues its execution from the point where it yielded, with the call to `coroutine.yield` returning any extra arguments passed to `coroutine.resume`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Like `coroutine.create`, the `coroutine.wrap` function also creates a coroutine, but instead of returning the coroutine itself, it returns a function that, when called, resumes the coroutine.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Any arguments passed to this function go as extra arguments to `coroutine.resume`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] `coroutine.wrap` returns all the values returned by `coroutine.resume`, except the first one (the boolean error code).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Unlike `coroutine.resume`, the function created by `coroutine.wrap` propagates any error to the caller.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In this case, the function also closes the coroutine (see `coroutine.close`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] You can also create and manipulate coroutines through the C API: see functions `lua_newthread`, `lua_resume`, and `lua_yield`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This section describes the lexis, the syntax, and the semantics of Lua.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In other words, this section describes which tokens are valid, how they can be combined, and what their combinations mean.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Language constructs will be explained using the usual extended BNF notation, in which {*a*} means 0 or more *a*'s, and [*a*] means an optional *a*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Non-terminals are shown like non-terminal, keywords are shown like **kword**, and other terminal symbols are shown like ‘**=**’.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The complete syntax of Lua can be found in §9 at the end of this manual.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] It ignores spaces and comments between lexical elements (tokens), except as delimiters between two tokens.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In source code, Lua recognizes as spaces the standard ASCII whitespace characters space, form feed, newline, carriage return, horizontal tab, and vertical tab.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua is a case-sensitive language: `and` is a reserved word, but `And` and `AND` are two different, valid names.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] As a convention, programs should avoid creating names that start with an underscore followed by one or more uppercase letters (such as `_VERSION`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A backslash followed by a line break results in a newline in the string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The escape sequence '`\z`' skips the following span of whitespace characters, including line breaks; it is particularly useful to break and indent a long literal string into multiple lines without adding the newlines and spaces into the string contents.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A short literal string cannot contain unescaped line breaks nor escapes not forming a valid escape sequence.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] We can specify any byte in a short literal string, including embedded zeros, by its numeric value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This can be done with the escape sequence `\x*XX*`, where *XX* is a sequence of exactly two hexadecimal digits, or with the escape sequence `\*ddd*`, where *ddd* is a sequence of up to three decimal digits.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The UTF-8 encoding of a Unicode character can be inserted in a literal string with the escape sequence `\u{*XXX*}` (with mandatory enclosing braces), where *XXX* is a sequence of one or more hexadecimal digits representing the character code point.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This code point can be any value less than *231*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Literal strings can also be defined using a long format enclosed by *long brackets*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] We define an *opening long bracket of level *n** as an opening square bracket followed by *n* equal signs followed by another opening square bracket.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] So, an opening long bracket of level 0 is written as `[[`, an opening long bracket of level 1 is written as `[=[`, and so on.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A *closing long bracket* is defined similarly; for instance, a closing long bracket of level 4 is written as `]====]`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A *long literal* starts with an opening long bracket of any level and ends at the first closing long bracket of the same level.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] It can contain any text except a closing bracket of the same level.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Literals in this bracketed form can run for several lines, do not interpret any escape sequences, and ignore long brackets of any other level.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Any kind of end-of-line sequence (carriage return, newline, carriage return followed by newline, or newline followed by carriage return) is converted to a simple newline.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] When the opening long bracket is immediately followed by a newline, the newline is not included in the string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Any byte in a literal string not explicitly affected by the previous rules represents itself.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] However, Lua opens files for parsing in text mode, and the system's file functions may have problems with some control characters.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] So, it is safer to represent binary data as a quoted literal with explicit escape sequences for the non-text characters.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A *numeric constant* (or *numeral*) can be written with an optional fractional part and an optional decimal exponent, marked by a letter '`e`' or '`E`'.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua also accepts hexadecimal constants, which start with `0x` or `0X`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Hexadecimal constants also accept an optional fractional part plus an optional binary exponent, marked by a letter '`p`' or '`P`' and written in decimal.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A numeric constant with a radix point or an exponent denotes a float; otherwise, if its value fits in an integer or it is a hexadecimal constant, it denotes an integer; otherwise (that is, a decimal integer numeral that overflows), it denotes a float.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Hexadecimal numerals with neither a radix point nor an exponent always denote an integer value; if the value overflows, it *wraps around* to fit into a valid integer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A *comment* starts with a double hyphen (`--`) anywhere outside a string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If the text immediately after `--` is not an opening long bracket, the comment is a *short comment*, which runs until the end of the line.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Otherwise, it is a *long comment*, which runs until the corresponding closing long bracket.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] There are three kinds of variables in Lua: global variables, local variables, and table fields.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Any variable name is assumed to be global unless explicitly declared as a local (see §3.3.7).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Local variables are *lexically scoped*: local variables can be freely accessed by functions defined inside their scope (see §3.5).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Before the first assignment to a variable, its value is **nil**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The meaning of accesses to table fields can be changed via metatables (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] An access to a global variable `x` is equivalent to `_ENV.x`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Due to the way that chunks are compiled, the variable `_ENV` itself is never global (see §2.2).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua supports an almost conventional set of statements, similar to those in other conventional languages.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This set includes blocks, assignments, control structures, function calls, and variable declarations.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Both function calls and assignments can start with an open parenthesis.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] This possibility leads to an ambiguity in Lua's grammar.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The current parser always sees such constructions in the first way, interpreting the open parenthesis as the start of the arguments to a call.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Explicit blocks are useful to control the scope of variable declarations.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Explicit blocks are also sometimes used to add a **return** statement in the middle of another block (see §3.3.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The unit of compilation of Lua is called a *chunk*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua handles a chunk as the body of an anonymous function with a variable number of arguments (see §3.4.11).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] As such, chunks can define local variables, receive arguments, and return values.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Moreover, such anonymous function is compiled as in the scope of an external local variable called `_ENV` (see §2.2).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The resulting function always has `_ENV` as its only external variable, even if it does not use that variable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A chunk can be stored in a file or in a string inside the host program.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] To execute a chunk, Lua first *loads* it, precompiling the chunk's code into instructions for a virtual machine, and then Lua executes the compiled code with an interpreter for the virtual machine.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Chunks can also be precompiled into binary form; see the program `luac` and the function `string.dump` for details.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Programs in source and compiled forms are interchangeable; Lua automatically detects the file type and acts accordingly (see `load`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Therefore, the syntax for assignment defines a list of variables on the left side and a list of expressions on the right side.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Before the assignment, the list of values is *adjusted* to the length of the list of variables (see §3.4.12).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If a variable is both assigned and read inside a multiple assignment, Lua ensures that all reads get the value of the variable before the assignment.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] sets `a[3]` to 20, without affecting `a[4]` because the `i` in `a[i]` is evaluated (to 3) before it is assigned 4.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] cyclically permutes the values of `x`, `y`, and `z`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Note that this guarantee covers only accesses syntactically inside the assignment statement.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If a function or a metamethod called during the assignment changes the value of a variable, Lua gives no guarantees about the order of that access.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] An assignment to a global name `x = val` is equivalent to the assignment `_ENV.x = val` (see §2.2).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The meaning of assignments to table fields and global variables (which are actually table fields, too) can be changed via metatables (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] Lua also has a **for** statement, in two flavors (see §3.3.5).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The condition expression of a control structure can return any value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] All values different from **nil** and **false** test true.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In particular, the number 0 and the empty string also test true.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] In the **repeat**–**until** loop, the inner block does not end at the **until** keyword, but only after the condition.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] So, the condition can refer to local variables declared inside the loop block.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The **goto** statement transfers the program control to a label.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A label is visible in the entire block where it is defined, except inside nested functions.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A goto can jump to any visible label as long as it does not enter into the scope of a local variable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A label should not be declared where a label with the same name is visible, even if this other label has been declared in an enclosing block.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] A **break** ends the innermost enclosing loop.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The **return** statement is used to return values from a function or a chunk (which is handled as an anonymous function).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The **return** statement can only be written as the last statement of a block.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] If it is necessary to **return** in the middle of a block, then an explicit inner block can be used, as in the idiom `do return end`, because now **return** is the last statement in its (inner) block.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The **for** statement has two forms: one numerical and one generic.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The numerical **for** loop repeats a block of code while a control variable goes through an arithmetic progression.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p01] The given identifier (Name) defines the control variable, which is a new variable local to the loop body (*block*).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The loop starts by evaluating once the three control expressions.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Their values are called respectively the *initial value*, the *limit*, and the *step*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If the step is absent, it defaults to 1.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If both the initial value and the step are integers, the loop is done with integers; note that the limit may not be an integer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Otherwise, the three values are converted to floats and the loop is done with floats.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Beware of floating-point accuracy in this case.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] After that initialization, the loop body is repeated with the value of the control variable going through an arithmetic progression, starting at the initial value, with a common difference given by the step.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A negative step makes a decreasing sequence; a step equal to zero raises an error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The loop continues while the value is less than or equal to the limit (greater than or equal to for a negative step).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If the initial value is already greater than the limit (or less than, if the step is negative), the body is not executed.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] For integer loops, the control variable never wraps around; instead, the loop ends in case of an overflow.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] You should not change the value of the control variable during the loop.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If you need its value after the loop, assign it to another variable before exiting the loop.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The generic **for** statement works over functions, called *iterators*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] On each iteration, the iterator function is called to produce a new value, stopping when this new value is **nil**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The names *var_i* declare loop variables local to the loop body.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The first of these variables is the *control variable*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The loop starts by evaluating *explist* to produce four values: an *iterator function*, a *state*, an initial value for the control variable, and a *closing value*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Then, at each iteration, Lua calls the iterator function with two arguments: the state and the control variable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The results from this call are then assigned to the loop variables, following the rules of multiple assignments (see §3.3.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If the control variable becomes **nil**, the loop terminates.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Otherwise, the body is executed and the loop goes to the next iteration.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The closing value behaves like a to-be-closed variable (see §3.3.8), which can be used to release resources when the loop ends.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Otherwise, it does not interfere with the loop.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] In this case, all returned values are thrown away.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Function calls are explained in §3.4.10.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Local variables can be declared anywhere inside a block.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If present, an initial assignment has the same semantics of a multiple assignment (see §3.3.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Otherwise, all variables are initialized with **nil**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] There are two possible attributes: `const`, which declares a constant variable, that is, a variable that cannot be assigned to after its initialization; and `close`, which declares a to-be-closed variable (see §3.3.8).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A list of variables can contain at most one to-be-closed variable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A chunk is also a block (see §3.3.2), and so local variables can be declared in a chunk outside any explicit block.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The visibility rules for local variables are explained in §3.5.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A to-be-closed variable behaves like a constant local variable, except that its value is *closed* whenever the variable goes out of scope, including normal block termination, exiting its block by **break**/**goto**/**return**, or exiting by an error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Here, to *close* a value means to call its `__close` metamethod.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When calling the metamethod, the value itself is passed as the first argument and the error object that caused the exit (if any) is passed as a second argument; if there was no error, the second argument is **nil**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The value assigned to a to-be-closed variable must have a `__close` metamethod or be a false value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If several to-be-closed variables go out of scope at the same event, they are closed in the reverse order that they were declared.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If there is any error while running a closing method, that error is handled like an error in the regular code where the variable was defined.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] After an error, the other pending closing methods will still be called.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If a coroutine yields and is never resumed again, some variables may never go out of scope, and therefore they will never be closed.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] (These variables are the ones created inside the coroutine and in scope at the point where the coroutine yielded.) Similarly, if a coroutine ends with an error, it does not unwind its stack, so it does not close any variable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] In both cases, you can either use finalizers or call `coroutine.close` to close the variables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] However, if the coroutine was created through `coroutine.wrap`, then its corresponding function will close the coroutine in case of errors.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Numerals and literal strings are explained in §3.1; variables are explained in §3.2; function definitions are explained in §3.4.11; function calls are explained in §3.4.10; table constructors are explained in §3.4.9.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Vararg expressions, denoted by three dots ('`...`'), can only be used when directly inside a variadic function; they are explained in §3.4.11.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Binary operators comprise arithmetic operators (see §3.4.1), bitwise operators (see §3.4.2), relational operators (see §3.4.4), logical operators (see §3.4.5), and the concatenation operator (see §3.4.6).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Unary operators comprise the unary minus (see §3.4.1), the unary bitwise NOT (see §3.4.2), the unary logical **not** (see §3.4.5), and the unary *length operator* (see §3.4.7).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] With the exception of exponentiation and float division, the arithmetic operators work as follows: If both operands are integers, the operation is performed over integers and the result is an integer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Otherwise, if both operands are numbers, then they are converted to floats, the operation is performed following the machine's rules for floating-point arithmetic (usually the IEEE 754 standard), and the result is a float.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Exponentiation and float division (`/`) always convert their operands to floats and the result is always a float.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Exponentiation uses the ISO C function `pow`, so that it works for non-integer exponents too.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Floor division (`//`) is a division that rounds the quotient towards minus infinity, resulting in the floor of the division of its operands.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Modulo is defined as the remainder of a division that rounds the quotient towards minus infinity (floor division).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] In case of overflows in integer arithmetic, all operations *wrap around*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] All bitwise operations convert its operands to integers (see §3.4.3), operate on all bits of those integers, and result in an integer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Both right and left shifts fill the vacant bits with zeros.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Negative displacements shift to the other direction; displacements with absolute values equal to or higher than the number of bits in an integer result in zero (as all bits are shifted out).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Lua provides some automatic conversions between some types and representations at run time.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Bitwise operators always convert float operands to integers.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Exponentiation and float division always convert integer operands to floats.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] All other arithmetic operations applied to mixed numbers (integers and floats) convert the integer operand to a float.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The C API also converts both integers to floats and floats to integers, as needed.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Moreover, string concatenation accepts numbers as arguments, besides strings.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] In a conversion from integer to float, if the integer value has an exact representation as a float, that is the result.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Otherwise, the conversion gets the nearest higher or the nearest lower representable value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The conversion from float to integer checks whether the float has an exact representation as an integer (that is, the float has an integral value and it is in the range of integer representation).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If it does, that representation is the result.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Several places in Lua coerce strings to numbers when necessary.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] In particular, the string library sets metamethods that try to coerce strings to numbers in all arithmetic operations.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If the conversion fails, the library calls the metamethod of the other operand (if present) or it raises an error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Note that bitwise operators do not do this coercion.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] It is always a good practice not to rely on the implicit coercions from strings to numbers, as they are not always applied; in particular, `"1"==1` is false and `"1"<1` raises an error (see §3.4.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] These coercions exist mainly for compatibility and may be removed in future versions of the language.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A string is converted to an integer or a float following its syntax and the rules of the Lua lexer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The string may have also leading and trailing whitespaces and a sign.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] All conversions from strings to numbers accept both a dot and the current locale mark as the radix character.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] (The Lua lexer, however, accepts only a dot.) If the string is not a valid numeral, the conversion fails.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If necessary, the result of this first step is then converted to a specific number subtype following the previous rules for conversions between floats and integers.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The conversion from numbers to strings uses a non-specified human-readable format.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] To convert numbers to strings in any specific way, use the function `string.format`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] These operators always result in **false** or **true**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Equality (`==`) first compares the type of its operands.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If the types are different, then the result is **false**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Otherwise, the values of the operands are compared.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Strings are equal if they have the same byte content.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Numbers are equal if they denote the same mathematical value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Tables, userdata, and threads are compared by reference: two objects are considered equal only if they are the same object.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Every time you create a new object (a table, a userdata, or a thread), this new object is different from any previously existing object.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Functions with any detectable difference (different behavior, different definition) are always different.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Functions created at different times but with no detectable differences may be classified as equal or not (depending on internal caching details).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] You can change the way that Lua compares tables and userdata by using the `__eq` metamethod (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Equality comparisons do not convert strings to numbers or vice versa.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Thus, `"0"==0` evaluates to **false**, and `t[0]` and `t["0"]` denote different entries in a table.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The operator `~=` is exactly the negation of equality (`==`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If both arguments are numbers, then they are compared according to their mathematical values, regardless of their subtypes.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Otherwise, if both arguments are strings, then their values are compared according to the current locale.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Otherwise, Lua tries to call the `__lt` or the `__le` metamethod (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A comparison `a > b` is translated to `b < a` and `a >= b` is translated to `b <= a`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Following the IEEE 754 standard, the special value NaN is considered neither less than, nor equal to, nor greater than any value, including itself.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The logical operators in Lua are **and**, **or**, and **not**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Like the control structures (see §3.3.4), all logical operators consider both **false** and **nil** as false and anything else as true.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The negation operator **not** always returns **false** or **true**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The conjunction operator **and** returns its first argument if this value is **false** or **nil**; otherwise, **and** returns its second argument.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The disjunction operator **or** returns its first argument if this value is different from **nil** and **false**; otherwise, **or** returns its second argument.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Both **and** and **or** use short-circuit evaluation; that is, the second operand is evaluated only if necessary.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The string concatenation operator in Lua is denoted by two dots ('`..`').
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If both operands are strings or numbers, then the numbers are converted to strings in a non-specified format (see §3.4.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Otherwise, the `__concat` metamethod is called (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The length operator is denoted by the unary prefix operator `#`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The length of a string is its number of bytes.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The length operator applied on a table returns a border in that table.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] In words, a border is any positive integer index present in the table that is followed by an absent index, plus two limit cases: zero, when index 1 is absent; and the maximum value for an integer, when that index is present.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Note that keys that are not positive integers do not interfere with borders.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A table with exactly one border is called a *sequence*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] For instance, the table `{10, 20, 30, 40, 50}` is a sequence, as it has only one border (5).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The table `{10, 20, 30, nil, 50}` has two borders (3 and 5), and therefore it is not a sequence.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] (The **nil** at index 4 is called a *hole*.) The table `{nil, 20, 30, nil, nil, 60, nil}` has three borders (0, 3, and 6), so it is not a sequence, too.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The table `{}` is a sequence with border 0.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When `t` is a sequence, `#t` returns its only border, which corresponds to the intuitive notion of the length of the sequence.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When `t` is not a sequence, `#t` can return any of its borders.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The computation of the length of a table has a guaranteed worst time of *O(log n)*, where *n* is the largest integer key in the table.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A program can modify the behavior of the length operator for any value but strings through the `__len` metamethod (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] As usual, you can use parentheses to change the precedences of an expression.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The concatenation ('`..`') and exponentiation ('`^`') operators are right associative.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] All other binary operators are left associative.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Table constructors are expressions that create tables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Every time a constructor is evaluated, a new table is created.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A constructor can be used to create an empty table or to create a table and initialize some of its fields.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Each field of the form `[exp1] = exp2` adds to the new table an entry with key `exp1` and value `exp2`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A field of the form `name = exp` is equivalent to `["name"] = exp`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Fields of the form `exp` are equivalent to `[i] = exp`, where `i` are consecutive integers starting with 1; fields in the other formats do not affect this counting.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The order of the assignments in a constructor is undefined.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If the last field in the list has the form `exp` and the expression is a multires expression, then all values returned by this expression enter the list consecutively (see §3.4.12).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The field list can have an optional trailing separator, as a convenience for machine-generated code.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] In a function call, first prefixexp and args are evaluated.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If the value of prefixexp has type *function*, then this function is called with the given arguments.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Otherwise, if present, the prefixexp `__call` metamethod is called: its first argument is the value of prefixexp, followed by the original call arguments (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A call `v:name(*args*)` is syntactic sugar for `v.name(v,*args*)`, except that `v` is evaluated only once.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] All argument expressions are evaluated before the call.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A call of the form `f{*fields*}` is syntactic sugar for `f({*fields*})`; that is, the argument list is a single new table.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A call of the form `f'*string*'` (or `f"*string*"` or `f[[*string*]]`) is syntactic sugar for `f('*string*')`; that is, the argument list is a single literal string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A call of the form `return *functioncall*` not in the scope of a to-be-closed variable is called a *tail call*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Lua implements *proper tail calls* (or *proper tail recursion*): In a tail call, the called function reuses the stack entry of the calling function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Therefore, there is no limit on the number of nested tail calls that a program can execute.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] However, a tail call erases any debug information about the calling function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Note that a tail call only happens with a particular syntax, where the **return** has one single function call as argument, and it is outside the scope of any to-be-closed variable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] This syntax makes the calling function return exactly the returns of the called function, without any intervening action.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A function definition is an executable expression, whose value has type *function*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When Lua precompiles a chunk, all its function bodies are precompiled too, but they are not created yet.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Then, whenever Lua executes the function definition, the function is *instantiated* (or *closed*).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] This function instance, or *closure*, is the final value of the expression.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When a Lua function is called, it adjusts its list of arguments to the length of its list of parameters (see §3.4.12), unless the function is a *variadic function*, which is indicated by three dots ('`...`') at the end of its parameter list.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A variadic function does not adjust its argument list; instead, it collects all extra arguments and supplies them to the function through a *vararg expression*, which is also written as three dots.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The value of this expression is a list of all actual extra arguments, similar to a function with multiple results (see §3.4.12).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Results are returned using the **return** statement (see §3.3.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If control reaches the end of a function without encountering a **return** statement, then the function returns with no results.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] There is a system-dependent limit on the number of values that a function may return.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] This limit is guaranteed to be greater than 1000.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The *colon* syntax is used to emulate *methods*, adding an implicit extra parameter `self` to the function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Both function calls and vararg expressions can result in multiple values.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] These expressions are called *multires expressions*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When a multires expression is used as the last element of a list of expressions, all results from the expression are added to the list of values produced by the list of expressions.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Note that a single expression in a place that expects a list of expressions is the last expression in that (singleton) list.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] These are the places where Lua expects a list of expressions: A **return** statement, for instance `return e1, e2, e3` (see §3.3.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The arguments of a function call, for instance `foo(e1, e2, e3)` (see §3.4.10).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A multiple assignment, for instance `a , b, c = e1, e2, e3` (see §3.3.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A local declaration, for instance `local a , b, c = e1, e2, e3` (see §3.3.7).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The initial values in a generic **for** loop, for instance `for k in e1, e2, e3 do ... end` (see §3.3.5).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The *adjustment* follows these rules: If there are more values than needed, the extra values are thrown away; if there are fewer values than needed, the list is extended with **nil**'s.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When the list of expressions ends with a multires expression, all results from that expression enter the list of values before the adjustment.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When a multires expression is used in a list of expressions without being the last element, or in a place where the syntax expects a single expression, Lua adjusts the result list of that expression to one element.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] As a particular case, the syntax expects a single expression inside a parenthesized expression; therefore, adding parentheses around a multires expression forces it to produce exactly one result.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] We seldom need to use a vararg expression in a place where the syntax expects a single expression.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] (Usually it is simpler to add a regular parameter before the variadic part and use that parameter.) When there is such a need, we recommend assigning the vararg expression to a single variable and using that variable in its place.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Here are some examples of uses of mutlres expressions.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The scope of a local variable begins at the first statement after its declaration and lasts until the last non-void statement of the innermost block that includes the declaration.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Notice that, in a declaration like `local x = x`, the new `x` being declared is not in scope yet, and so the second `x` refers to the outside variable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Because of the lexical scoping rules, local variables can be freely accessed by functions defined inside their scope.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A local variable used by an inner function is called an *upvalue* (or *external local variable*, or simply *external variable*) inside the inner function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Notice that each execution of a **local** statement defines new local variables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The loop creates ten closures (that is, ten instances of the anonymous function).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Each of these closures uses a different `y` variable, while all of them share the same `x`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] This section describes the C API for Lua, that is, the set of C functions available to the host program to communicate with Lua.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] All API functions and related types and constants are declared in the header file `lua.h`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Even when we use the term "function", any facility in the API may be provided as a macro instead.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Except where stated otherwise, all such macros use each of their arguments exactly once (except for the first argument, which is always a Lua state), and so do not generate any hidden side-effects.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] As in most C libraries, the Lua API functions do not check their arguments for validity or consistency.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] However, you can change this behavior by compiling Lua with the macro `LUA_USE_APICHECK` defined.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The Lua library is fully reentrant: it has no global variables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] It keeps all information it needs in a dynamic structure, called the *Lua state*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Each Lua state has one or more threads, which correspond to independent, cooperative lines of execution.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The type `lua_State` (despite its name) refers to a thread.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A pointer to a thread must be passed as the first argument to every function in the library, except to `lua_newstate`, which creates a Lua state from scratch and returns a pointer to the *main thread* in the new state.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Lua uses a *virtual stack* to pass values to and from C.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Each element in this stack represents a Lua value (**nil**, number, string, etc.).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Functions in the API can access this stack through the Lua state parameter that they receive.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Whenever Lua calls C, the called function gets a new stack, which is independent of previous stacks and of stacks of C functions that are still active.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] This stack initially contains any arguments to the C function and it is where the C function can store temporary Lua values and must push its results to be returned to the caller (see `lua_CFunction`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] For convenience, most query operations in the API do not follow a strict stack discipline.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Instead, they can refer to any element in the stack by using an *index*: A positive index represents an absolute stack position, starting at 1 as the bottom of the stack; a negative index represents an offset relative to the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When you interact with the Lua API, you are responsible for ensuring consistency.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] In particular, *you are responsible for controlling stack overflow*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When you call any API function, you must ensure the stack has enough room to accommodate the results.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] There is one exception to the above rule: When you call a Lua function without a fixed number of results (see `lua_call`), Lua ensures that the stack has enough space for all results.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] However, it does not ensure any extra space.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] So, before pushing anything on the stack after such a call you should use `lua_checkstack`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Whenever Lua calls C, it ensures that the stack has space for at least `LUA_MINSTACK` extra elements; that is, you can safely push up to `LUA_MINSTACK` values into it.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] `LUA_MINSTACK` is defined as 20, so that usually you do not have to worry about stack space unless your code has loops pushing elements onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Whenever necessary, you can use the function `lua_checkstack` to ensure that the stack has enough space for pushing new elements.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Any function in the API that receives stack indices works only with *valid indices* or *acceptable indices*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A *valid index* is an index that refers to a position that stores a modifiable Lua value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] It comprises stack indices between 1 and the stack top (`1 ≤ abs(index) ≤ top`) plus *pseudo-indices*, which represent some positions that are accessible to C code but that are not in the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Pseudo-indices are used to access the registry (see §4.3) and the upvalues of a C function (see §4.2).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Functions that do not need a specific mutable position, but only a value (e.g., query functions), can be called with acceptable indices.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] An *acceptable index* can be any valid index, but it also can be any positive index after the stack top within the space allocated for the stack, that is, indices up to the stack size.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] (Note that 0 is never an acceptable index.) Indices to upvalues (see §4.2) greater than the real number of upvalues in the current C function are also acceptable (but invalid).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Except when noted otherwise, functions in the API work with acceptable indices.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Acceptable indices serve to avoid extra tests against the stack top when querying the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] For instance, a C function can query its third argument without the need to check whether there is a third argument, that is, without the need to check whether 3 is a valid index.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] For functions that can be called with acceptable indices, any non-valid index is treated as if it contains a value of a virtual type `LUA_TNONE`, which behaves like a nil value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Several functions in the API return pointers (`const char*`) to Lua strings in the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] (See `lua_pushfstring`, `lua_pushlstring`, `lua_pushstring`, and `lua_tolstring`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] In general, Lua's garbage collection can free or move internal memory and then invalidate pointers to internal strings.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] To allow a safe use of these pointers, the API guarantees that any pointer to a string in a stack index is valid while the string value at that index is not removed from the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] (It can be moved to another index, though.) When the index is a pseudo-index (referring to an upvalue), the pointer is valid while the corresponding call is active and the corresponding upvalue is not modified.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Some functions in the debug interface also return pointers to strings, namely `lua_getlocal`, `lua_getupvalue`, `lua_setlocal`, and `lua_setupvalue`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] For these functions, the pointer is guaranteed to be valid while the caller function is active and the given closure (if one was given) is in the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Except for these guarantees, the garbage collector is free to invalidate any pointer to internal strings.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When a C function is created, it is possible to associate some values with it, thus creating a *C closure* (see `lua_pushcclosure`); these values are called *upvalues* and are accessible to the function whenever it is called.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Whenever a C function is called, its upvalues are located at specific pseudo-indices.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] These pseudo-indices are produced by the macro `lua_upvalueindex`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The first upvalue associated with a function is at index `lua_upvalueindex(1)`, and so on.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Any access to `lua_upvalueindex(*n*)`, where *n* is greater than the number of upvalues of the current function (but not greater than 256, which is one plus the maximum number of upvalues in a closure), produces an acceptable but invalid index.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A C closure can also change the values of its corresponding upvalues.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Lua provides a *registry*, a predefined table that can be used by any C code to store whatever Lua values it needs to store.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The registry table is always accessible at pseudo-index `LUA_REGISTRYINDEX`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Any C library can store data into this table, but it must take care to choose keys that are different from those used by other libraries, to avoid collisions.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Typically, you should use as key a string containing your library name, or a light userdata with the address of a C object in your code, or any Lua object created by your code.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] As with variable names, string keys starting with an underscore followed by uppercase letters are reserved for Lua.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The integer keys in the registry are used by the reference mechanism (see `luaL_ref`) and by some predefined values.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Therefore, integer keys in the registry must not be used for other purposes.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When you create a new Lua state, its registry comes with some predefined values.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] These predefined values are indexed with integer keys defined as constants in `lua.h`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The following constants are defined: **`LUA_RIDX_MAINTHREAD`:** At this index the registry has the main thread of the state.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] (The main thread is the one created together with the state.) **`LUA_RIDX_GLOBALS`:** At this index the registry has the global environment.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Internally, Lua uses the C `longjmp` facility to handle errors.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] (Lua will use exceptions if you compile it as C++; search for `LUAI_THROW` in the source code for details.) When Lua faces any error, such as a memory allocation error or a type error, it *raises* an error; that is, it does a long jump.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] A *protected environment* uses `setjmp` to set a recovery point; any error jumps to the most recent active recovery point.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Inside a C function you can raise an error explicitly by calling `lua_error`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Most functions in the API can raise an error, for instance due to a memory allocation error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The documentation for each function indicates whether it can raise errors.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If an error happens outside any protected environment, Lua calls a *panic function* (see `lua_atpanic`) and then calls `abort`, thus exiting the host application.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Your panic function can avoid this exit by never returning (e.g., doing a long jump to your own recovery point outside Lua).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The panic function, as its name implies, is a mechanism of last resort.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] As a general rule, when a C function is called by Lua with a Lua state, it can do whatever it wants on that Lua state, as it should be already protected.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] However, when C code operates on other Lua states (e.g., a Lua-state argument to the function, a Lua state stored in the registry, or the result of `lua_newthread`), it should use them only in API calls that cannot raise errors.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The panic function runs as if it were a message handler (see §2.3); in particular, the error object is on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] However, there is no guarantee about stack space.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] To push anything on the stack, the panic function must first check the available space (see §4.1.1).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Several functions that report errors in the API use the following status codes to indicate different kinds of errors or other conditions: **`LUA_OK` (0):** no errors.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] **`LUA_ERRMEM`:** memory allocation error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] For such errors, Lua does not call the message handler.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] **`LUA_ERRERR`:** error while running the message handler.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] **`LUA_ERRSYNTAX`:** syntax error during precompilation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] **`LUA_YIELD`:** the thread (coroutine) yields.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] **`LUA_ERRFILE`:** a file-related error; e.g., it cannot open or read the file.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] These constants are defined in the header file `lua.h`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Internally, Lua uses the C `longjmp` facility to yield a coroutine.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Therefore, if a C function `foo` calls an API function and this API function yields (directly or indirectly by calling another function that yields), Lua cannot return to `foo` any more, because the `longjmp` removes its frame from the C stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] To avoid this kind of problem, Lua raises an error whenever it tries to yield across an API call, except for three functions: `lua_yieldk`, `lua_callk`, and `lua_pcallk`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] All those functions receive a *continuation function* (as a parameter named `k`) to continue execution after a yield.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] We need to set some terminology to explain continuations.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] We have a C function called from Lua which we will call the *original function*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] This original function then calls one of those three functions in the C API, which we will call the *callee function*, that then yields the current thread.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] This can happen when the callee function is `lua_yieldk`, or when the callee function is either `lua_callk` or `lua_pcallk` and the function called by them yields.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Suppose the running thread yields while executing the callee function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] After the thread resumes, it eventually will finish running the callee function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] However, the callee function cannot return to the original function, because its frame in the C stack was destroyed by the yield.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Instead, Lua calls a *continuation function*, which was given as an argument to the callee function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] As the name implies, the continuation function should continue the task of the original function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Now we want to allow the Lua code being run by `lua_pcall` to yield.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] In the above code, the new function `k` is a *continuation function* (with type `lua_KFunction`), which should do all the work that the original function was doing after calling `lua_pcall`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Note the external, explicit call to the continuation: Lua will call the continuation only if needed, that is, in case of errors or resuming after a yield.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] If the called function returns normally without ever yielding, `lua_pcallk` (and `lua_callk`) will also return normally.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Besides the Lua state, the continuation function has two other parameters: the final status of the call and the context value (`ctx`) that was passed originally to `lua_pcallk`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Lua does not use this context value; it only passes this value from the original function to the continuation function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] For `lua_pcallk`, the status is the same value that would be returned by `lua_pcallk`, except that it is `LUA_YIELD` when being executed after a yield (instead of `LUA_OK`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] For `lua_yieldk` and `lua_callk`, the status is always `LUA_YIELD` when Lua calls the continuation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] (For these two functions, Lua will not call the continuation in case of errors, because they do not handle errors.) Similarly, when using `lua_callk`, you should call the continuation function with `LUA_OK` as the status.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Lua treats the continuation function as if it were the original function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The continuation function receives the same Lua stack from the original function, in the same state it would be if the callee function had returned.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] (For instance, after a `lua_callk` the function and its arguments are removed from the stack and replaced by the results from the call.) It also has the same upvalues.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Whatever it returns is handled by Lua as if it were the return of the original function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Here we list all functions and types from the C API in alphabetical order.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The first field, `o`, is how many elements the function pops from the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The second field, `p`, is how many elements the function pushes onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Converts the acceptable index `idx` into an equivalent absolute index (that is, one that does not depend on the stack size).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The type of the memory-allocation function used by Lua states.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The allocator function must provide a functionality similar to `realloc`, but not exactly the same.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Its arguments are `ud`, an opaque pointer passed to `lua_newstate`; `ptr`, a pointer to the block being allocated/reallocated/freed; `osize`, the original size of the block or some code about what is being allocated; and `nsize`, the new size of the block.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When `ptr` is not `NULL`, `osize` is the size of the block pointed by `ptr`, that is, the size given when it was allocated or reallocated.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When `ptr` is `NULL`, `osize` encodes the kind of object that Lua is allocating.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] `osize` is any of `LUA_TSTRING`, `LUA_TTABLE`, `LUA_TFUNCTION`, `LUA_TUSERDATA`, or `LUA_TTHREAD` when (and only when) Lua is creating a new object of that type.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When `osize` is some other value, Lua is allocating memory for something else.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When `nsize` is zero, the allocator must behave like `free` and then return `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] When `nsize` is not zero, the allocator must behave like `realloc`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] In particular, the allocator returns `NULL` if and only if it cannot fulfill the request.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Here is a simple implementation for the allocator function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Note that ISO C ensures that `free(NULL)` has no effect and that `realloc(NULL,size)` is equivalent to `malloc(size)`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Performs an arithmetic or bitwise operation over the two values (or one, in the case of negations) at the top of the stack, with the value on the top being the second operand, pops these values, and pushes the result of the operation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] The function follows the semantics of the corresponding Lua operator (that is, it may call metamethods).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Sets a new panic function and returns the old one (see §4.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] Like regular Lua calls, `lua_call` respects the `__call` metamethod.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p02] So, here the word "function" means any callable value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] To do a call you must use the following protocol: first, the function to be called is pushed onto the stack; then, the arguments to the call are pushed in direct order; that is, the first argument is pushed first.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Finally you call `lua_call`; `nargs` is the number of arguments that you pushed onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] When the function returns, all arguments and the function value are popped and the call results are pushed onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The number of results is adjusted to `nresults`, unless `nresults` is `LUA_MULTRET`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] In this case, all results from the function are pushed; Lua takes care that the returned values fit into the stack space, but it does not ensure any extra space in the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The function results are pushed onto the stack in direct order (the first result is pushed first), so that after the call the last result is on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Any error while calling and running the function is propagated upwards (with a `longjmp`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Note that the code above is *balanced*: at its end, the stack is back to its original configuration.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This is considered good programming practice.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function behaves exactly like `lua_call`, but allows the called function to yield (see §4.5).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] In order to communicate properly with Lua, a C function must use the following protocol, which defines the way parameters and results are passed: a C function receives its arguments from Lua in its stack in direct order (the first argument is pushed first).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] So, when the function starts, `lua_gettop(L)` returns the number of arguments received by the function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The first argument (if any) is at index 1 and its last argument is at index `lua_gettop(L)`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] To return values to Lua, a C function just pushes them onto the stack, in direct order (the first result is pushed first), and returns in C the number of results.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Any other value in the stack below the results will be properly discarded by Lua.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Like a Lua function, a C function called by Lua can also return many results.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Ensures that the stack has space for at least `n` extra elements, that is, that you can safely push up to `n` values into it.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] It returns false if it cannot fulfill the request, either because it would cause the stack to be greater than a fixed maximum size (typically at least several thousand elements) or because it cannot allocate memory for the extra space.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function never shrinks the stack; if the stack already has space for the extra elements, it is left unchanged.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Close all active to-be-closed variables in the main thread, release all objects in the given Lua state (calling the corresponding garbage-collection metamethods, if any), and frees all dynamic memory used by this state.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] On several platforms, you may not need to call this function, because all resources are naturally released when the host program ends.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] On the other hand, long-running programs that create multiple states, such as daemons or web servers, will probably need to close states as soon as they are not needed.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Close the to-be-closed slot at the given index and set its value to **nil**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The index must be the last index previously marked to be closed (see `lua_toclose`) that is still active (that is, not closed yet).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] A `__close` metamethod cannot yield when called through this function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Resets a thread, cleaning its call stack and closing all pending to-be-closed variables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns a status code: `LUA_OK` for no errors in the thread (either the original error that stopped the thread or errors in closing methods), or an error status otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] In case of error, leaves the error object on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The parameter `from` represents the coroutine that is resetting `L`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If there is no such coroutine, this parameter can be `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at index `index1` satisfies `op` when compared with the value at index `index2`, following the semantics of the corresponding Lua operator (that is, it may call metamethods).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Also returns 0 if any of the indices is not valid.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Concatenates the `n` values at the top of the stack, pops them, and leaves the result on the top.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If `n` is 1, the result is the single value on the stack (that is, the function does nothing); if `n` is 0, the result is the empty string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Concatenation is performed following the usual semantics of Lua (see §3.4.6).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Copies the element at index `fromidx` into the valid index `toidx`, replacing the value at that position.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Values at other positions are not affected.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Creates a new empty table and pushes it onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Parameter `narr` is a hint for how many elements the table will have as a sequence; parameter `nrec` is a hint for how many other elements the table will have.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Lua may use these hints to preallocate memory for the new table.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This preallocation may help performance when you know in advance how many elements the table will have.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Otherwise you can use the function `lua_newtable`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Receives a Lua function on the top of the stack and produces a binary chunk that, if loaded again, results in a function equivalent to the one dumped.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] As it produces parts of the chunk, `lua_dump` calls function `writer` (see `lua_Writer`) with the given `data` to write them.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If `strip` is true, the binary representation may not include all debug information about the function, to save space.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The value returned is the error code returned by the last call to the writer; 0 means no errors.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function does not pop the Lua function from the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Raises a Lua error, using the value on the top of the stack as the error object.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function does a long jump, and therefore never returns (see `luaL_error`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function performs several tasks, according to the value of the parameter `what`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] For options that need extra arguments, they are listed after the option.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] **`LUA_GCCOLLECT`:** Performs a full garbage-collection cycle.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] **`LUA_GCSTOP`:** Stops the garbage collector.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] **`LUA_GCRESTART`:** Restarts the garbage collector.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] **`LUA_GCCOUNT`:** Returns the current amount of memory (in Kbytes) in use by Lua.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] **`LUA_GCCOUNTB`:** Returns the remainder of dividing the current amount of bytes of memory in use by Lua by 1024.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] **`LUA_GCSTEP` `(int stepsize)`:** Performs an incremental step of garbage collection, corresponding to the allocation of `stepsize` Kbytes.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] **`LUA_GCISRUNNING`:** Returns a boolean that tells whether the collector is running (i.e., not stopped).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] **`LUA_GCINC` (int pause, int stepmul, stepsize):** Changes the collector to incremental mode with the given parameters (see §2.5.1).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns the previous mode (`LUA_GCGEN` or `LUA_GCINC`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] **`LUA_GCGEN` (int minormul, int majormul):** Changes the collector to generational mode with the given parameters (see §2.5.2).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] For more details about these options, see `collectgarbage`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function should not be called by a finalizer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns the memory-allocation function of a given state.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If `ud` is not `NULL`, Lua stores in `*ud` the opaque pointer given when the memory-allocator function was set.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes onto the stack the value `t[k]`, where `t` is the value at the given index.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] As in Lua, this function may trigger a metamethod for the "index" event (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns a pointer to a raw memory area associated with the given Lua state.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The application can use this area for any purpose; Lua does not use it for anything.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Each new thread has this area initialized with a copy of the area of the main thread.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] By default, this area has the size of a pointer to void, but you can recompile Lua with a different size for this area.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes onto the stack the value of the global `name`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes onto the stack the value `t[i]`, where `t` is the value at the given index.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If the value at the given index has a metatable, the function pushes that metatable onto the stack and returns 1.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Otherwise, the function returns 0 and pushes nothing on the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes onto the stack the value `t[k]`, where `t` is the value at the given index and `k` is the value on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function pops the key from the stack, pushing the resulting value in its place.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns the index of the top element in the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Because indices start at 1, this result is equal to the number of elements in the stack; in particular, 0 means an empty stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes onto the stack the `n`-th user value associated with the full userdata at the given index and returns the type of the pushed value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If the userdata does not have that value, pushes **nil** and returns `LUA_TNONE`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Moves the top element into the given valid index, shifting up the elements above this index to open space.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function cannot be called with a pseudo-index, because a pseudo-index is not an actual stack position.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] By default this type is `long long`, (usually a 64-bit two-complement integer), but that can be changed to `long` or `int` (usually a 32-bit two-complement integer).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Lua also defines the constants `LUA_MININTEGER` and `LUA_MAXINTEGER`, with the minimum and the maximum values that fit in this type.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at the given index is a boolean, and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at the given index is a C function, and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at the given index is a function (either C or Lua), and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at the given index is an integer (that is, the value is a number and is represented as an integer), and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at the given index is a light userdata, and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at the given index is **nil**, and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the given index is not valid, and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the given index is not valid or if the value at this index is **nil**, and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at the given index is a number or a string convertible to a number, and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at the given index is a string or a number (which is always convertible to a string), and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at the given index is a table, and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at the given index is a thread, and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the value at the given index is a userdata (either full or light), and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the given coroutine can yield, and 0 otherwise.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The type for continuation-function contexts.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This type is defined as `intptr_t` when `intptr_t` is available, so that it can store pointers too.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Otherwise, it is defined as `ptrdiff_t`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Type for continuation functions (see §4.5).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns the length of the value at the given index.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] It is equivalent to the '`#`' operator in Lua (see §3.4.7) and may trigger a metamethod for the "length" event (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If there are no errors, `lua_load` pushes the compiled chunk as a Lua function on top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The `lua_load` function uses a user-supplied `reader` function to read the chunk (see `lua_Reader`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The `data` argument is an opaque value passed to the reader function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The `chunkname` argument gives a name to the chunk, which is used for error messages and in debug information (see §4.7).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] `lua_load` automatically detects whether the chunk is text or binary and loads it accordingly (see program `luac`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The string `mode` works as in function `load`, with the addition that a `NULL` value is equivalent to the string "`bt`".
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] `lua_load` uses the stack internally, so the reader function must always leave the stack unmodified when returning.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] `lua_load` can return `LUA_OK`, `LUA_ERRSYNTAX`, or `LUA_ERRMEM`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The function may also return other values corresponding to errors raised by the read function (see §4.4.1).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If the resulting function has upvalues, its first upvalue is set to the value of the global environment stored at index `LUA_RIDX_GLOBALS` in the registry (see §4.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] When loading main chunks, this upvalue will be the `_ENV` variable (see §2.2).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Other upvalues are initialized with **nil**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Creates a new independent state and returns its main thread.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns `NULL` if it cannot create the state (due to lack of memory).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The argument `f` is the allocator function; Lua will do all memory allocation for this state through this function (see `lua_Alloc`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The second argument, `ud`, is an opaque pointer that Lua passes to the allocator in every call.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] It is equivalent to `lua_createtable(L, 0, 0)`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Creates a new thread, pushes it on the stack, and returns a pointer to a `lua_State` that represents this new thread.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The new thread returned by this function shares with the original thread its global environment, but has an independent execution stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Threads are subject to garbage collection, like any Lua object.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function creates and pushes on the stack a new full userdata, with `nuvalue` associated Lua values, called `user values`, plus an associated block of raw memory with `size` bytes.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The function returns the address of the block of memory.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Lua ensures that this address is valid as long as the corresponding userdata is alive (see §2.5).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Moreover, if the userdata is marked for finalization (see §2.5.3), its address is valid at least until the call to its finalizer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pops a key from the stack, and pushes a key–value pair from the table at the given index, the "next" pair after the given key.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If there are no more elements in the table, then `lua_next` returns 0 and pushes nothing.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] While traversing a table, avoid calling `lua_tolstring` directly on a key, unless you know that the key is actually a string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Recall that `lua_tolstring` may change the value at the given index; this confuses the next call to `lua_next`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function may raise an error if the given key is neither **nil** nor present in the table.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] See function `next` for the caveats of modifying the table during its traversal.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] By default this type is double, but that can be changed to a single float or a long double.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Tries to convert a Lua float to a Lua integer; the float `n` must have an integral value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If that value is within the range of Lua integers, it is converted to an integer and assigned to `*p`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The macro results in a boolean indicating whether the conversion was successful.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This macro may evaluate its arguments more than once.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Calls a function (or a callable object) in protected mode.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Both `nargs` and `nresults` have the same meaning as in `lua_call`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If there are no errors during the call, `lua_pcall` behaves exactly like `lua_call`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] However, if there is any error, `lua_pcall` catches it, pushes a single value on the stack (the error object), and returns an error code.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Like `lua_call`, `lua_pcall` always removes the function and its arguments from the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If `msgh` is 0, then the error object returned on the stack is exactly the original error object.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Otherwise, `msgh` is the stack index of a *message handler*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] (This index cannot be a pseudo-index.) In case of runtime errors, this handler will be called with the error object and its return value will be the object returned on the stack by `lua_pcall`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Typically, the message handler is used to add more debug information to the error object, such as a stack traceback.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Such information cannot be gathered after the return of `lua_pcall`, since by then the stack has unwound.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The `lua_pcall` function returns one of the following status codes: `LUA_OK`, `LUA_ERRRUN`, `LUA_ERRMEM`, or `LUA_ERRERR`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function behaves exactly like `lua_pcall`, except that it allows the called function to yield (see §4.5).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] It is implemented as a macro over `lua_settop`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes a boolean value with value `b` onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function receives a pointer to a C function and pushes onto the stack a Lua value of type `function` that, when called, invokes the corresponding C function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The parameter `n` tells how many upvalues this function will have (see §4.2).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Any function to be callable by Lua must follow the correct protocol to receive its parameters and return its results (see `lua_CFunction`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] When a C function is created, it is possible to associate some values with it, the so called upvalues; these upvalues are then accessible to the function whenever it is called.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This association is called a C closure (see §4.2).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] To create a C closure, first the initial values for its upvalues must be pushed onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] (When there are multiple upvalues, the first value is pushed first.) Then `lua_pushcclosure` is called to create and push the C function onto the stack, with the argument `n` telling how many values will be associated with the function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] `lua_pushcclosure` also pops these values from the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] When `n` is zero, this function creates a *light C function*, which is just a pointer to the C function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] In that case, it never raises a memory error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function is equivalent to `lua_pushcclosure` with no upvalues.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes onto the stack a formatted string and returns a pointer to this string (see §4.1.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] It is similar to the ISO C function `sprintf`, but has two important differences.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] First, you do not have to allocate space for the result; the result is a Lua string and Lua takes care of memory allocation (and deallocation, through garbage collection).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Second, the conversion specifiers are quite restricted.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] There are no flags, widths, or precisions.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function may raise errors due to memory overflow or an invalid conversion specifier.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes the global environment onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes an integer with value `n` onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] A *light userdata* represents a pointer, a `void*`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] It is a value (like a number): you do not create it, it has no individual metatable, and it is not collected (as it was never created).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] A light userdata is equal to "any" light userdata with the same C address.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This macro is equivalent to `lua_pushstring`, but should be used only when `s` is a literal string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes the string pointed to by `s` with size `len` onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Lua will make or reuse an internal copy of the given string, so the memory at `s` can be freed or reused immediately after the function returns.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The string can contain any binary data, including embedded zeros.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns a pointer to the internal copy of the string (see §4.1.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes a float with value `n` onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes the zero-terminated string pointed to by `s` onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If `s` is `NULL`, pushes **nil** and returns `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes the thread represented by `L` onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if this thread is the main thread of its state.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes a copy of the element at the given index onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Equivalent to `lua_pushfstring`, except that it receives a `va_list` instead of a variable number of arguments.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 1 if the two values in indices `index1` and `index2` are primitively equal (that is, equal without calling the `__eq` metamethod).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Also returns 0 if any of the indices are not valid.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Similar to `lua_gettable`, but does a raw access (i.e., without metamethods).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes onto the stack the value `t[n]`, where `t` is the table at the given index.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The access is raw, that is, it does not use the `__index` metavalue.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pushes onto the stack the value `t[k]`, where `t` is the table at the given index and `k` is the pointer `p` represented as a light userdata.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The access is raw; that is, it does not use the `__index` metavalue.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns the raw "length" of the value at the given index: for strings, this is the string length; for tables, this is the result of the length operator ('`#`') with no metamethods; for userdata, this is the size of the block of memory allocated for the userdata.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Similar to `lua_settable`, but does a raw assignment (i.e., without metamethods).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Does the equivalent of `t[i] = v`, where `t` is the table at the given index and `v` is the value on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function pops the value from the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The assignment is raw, that is, it does not use the `__newindex` metavalue.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Does the equivalent of `t[p] = v`, where `t` is the table at the given index, `p` is encoded as a light userdata, and `v` is the value on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Every time `lua_load` needs another piece of the chunk, it calls the reader, passing along its `data` parameter.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The reader must return a pointer to a block of memory with a new piece of the chunk and set `size` to the block size.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The block must exist until the reader function is called again.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] To signal the end of the chunk, the reader must return `NULL` or set `size` to zero.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The reader function may return pieces of any size greater than zero.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Sets the C function `f` as the new value of global `name`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Removes the element at the given valid index, shifting down the elements above this index to fill the gap.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Moves the top element into the given valid index without shifting any element (therefore replacing the value at that given index), and then pops the top element.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function is deprecated; it is equivalent to `lua_closethread` with `from` being `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Starts and resumes a coroutine in the given thread `L`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] To start a coroutine, you push the main function plus any arguments onto the empty stack of the thread. then you call `lua_resume`, with `nargs` being the number of arguments.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This call returns when the coroutine suspends or finishes its execution.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] When it returns, `*nresults` is updated and the top of the stack contains the `*nresults` values passed to `lua_yield` or returned by the body function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] `lua_resume` returns `LUA_YIELD` if the coroutine yields, `LUA_OK` if the coroutine finishes its execution without errors, or an error code in case of errors (see §4.4.1).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] In case of errors, the error object is on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] To resume a coroutine, you remove the `*nresults` yielded values from its stack, push the values to be passed as results from `yield`, and then call `lua_resume`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The parameter `from` represents the coroutine that is resuming `L`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Rotates the stack elements between the valid index `idx` and the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The elements are rotated `n` positions in the direction of the top, for a positive `n`, or `-n` positions in the direction of the bottom, for a negative `n`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The absolute value of `n` must not be greater than the size of the slice being rotated.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Changes the allocator function of a given state to `f` with user data `ud`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Does the equivalent to `t[k] = v`, where `t` is the value at the given index and `v` is the value on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] As in Lua, this function may trigger a metamethod for the "newindex" event (see §2.4).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pops a value from the stack and sets it as the new value of global `name`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Does the equivalent to `t[n] = v`, where `t` is the value at the given index and `v` is the value on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pops a value from the stack and sets it as the new `n`-th user value associated to the full userdata at the given index.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns 0 if the userdata does not have that value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Pops a table or **nil** from the stack and sets that value as the new metatable for the value at the given index.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Does the equivalent to `t[k] = v`, where `t` is the value at the given index, `v` is the value on the top of the stack, and `k` is the value just below the top.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function pops both the key and the value from the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Accepts any index, or 0, and sets the stack top to this index.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If the new top is greater than the old one, then the new elements are filled with **nil**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If `index` is 0, then all stack elements are removed.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function can run arbitrary code when removing an index marked as to-be-closed from the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Sets the warning function to be used by Lua to emit warnings (see `lua_WarnFunction`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The `ud` parameter sets the value `ud` passed to the warning function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] An opaque structure that points to a thread and indirectly (through the thread) to the whole state of a Lua interpreter.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] All information about a state is accessible through this structure.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] A pointer to this structure must be passed as the first argument to every function in the library, except to `lua_newstate`, which creates a Lua state from scratch.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The status can be `LUA_OK` for a normal thread, an error code if the thread finished the execution of a `lua_resume` with an error, or `LUA_YIELD` if the thread is suspended.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] You can call functions only in threads with status `LUA_OK`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] You can resume threads with status `LUA_OK` (to start a new coroutine) or `LUA_YIELD` (to resume a coroutine).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Converts the zero-terminated string `s` to a number, pushes that number into the stack, and returns the total size of the string, that is, its length plus one.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The conversion can result in an integer or a float, according to the lexical conventions of Lua (see §3.1).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The string may have leading and trailing whitespaces and a sign.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If the string is not a valid numeral, returns 0 and pushes nothing.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Converts the Lua value at the given index to a C boolean value (0 or 1).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Like all tests in Lua, `lua_toboolean` returns true for any Lua value different from **false** and **nil**; otherwise it returns false.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Converts a value at the given index to a C function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] That value must be a C function; otherwise, returns `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Marks the given index in the stack as a to-be-closed slot (see §3.3.8).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Like a to-be-closed variable in Lua, the value at that slot in the stack will be closed when it goes out of scope.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Here, in the context of a C function, to go out of scope means that the running function returns to Lua, or there is an error, or the slot is removed from the stack through `lua_settop` or `lua_pop`, or there is a call to `lua_closeslot`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] A slot marked as to-be-closed should not be removed from the stack by any other function in the API except `lua_settop` or `lua_pop`, unless previously deactivated by `lua_closeslot`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function raises an error if the value at the given slot neither has a `__close` metamethod nor is a false value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function should not be called for an index that is equal to or below an active to-be-closed slot.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Note that, both in case of errors and of a regular return, by the time the `__close` metamethod runs, the C stack was already unwound, so that any automatic C variable declared in the calling function (e.g., a buffer) will be out of scope.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Equivalent to `lua_tointegerx` with `isnum` equal to `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Converts the Lua value at the given index to the signed integral type `lua_Integer`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The Lua value must be an integer, or a number or string convertible to an integer (see §3.4.3); otherwise, `lua_tointegerx` returns 0.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If `isnum` is not `NULL`, its referent is assigned a boolean value that indicates whether the operation succeeded.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Converts the Lua value at the given index to a C string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If `len` is not `NULL`, it sets `*len` with the string length.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The Lua value must be a string or a number; otherwise, the function returns `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If the value is a number, then `lua_tolstring` also *changes the actual value in the stack to a string*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] `lua_tolstring` returns a pointer to a string inside the Lua state (see §4.1.3).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This string always has a zero ('`\0`') after its last character (as in C), but can contain other zeros in its body.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function can raise memory errors only when converting a number to a string (as then it may create a new string).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Equivalent to `lua_tonumberx` with `isnum` equal to `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Converts the Lua value at the given index to the C type `lua_Number` (see `lua_Number`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The Lua value must be a number or a string convertible to a number (see §3.4.3); otherwise, `lua_tonumberx` returns 0.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Converts the value at the given index to a generic C pointer (`void*`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The value can be a userdata, a table, a thread, a string, or a function; otherwise, `lua_topointer` returns `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Different objects will give different pointers.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] There is no way to convert the pointer back to its original value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Typically this function is used only for hashing and debug information.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Equivalent to `lua_tolstring` with `len` equal to `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Converts the value at the given index to a Lua thread (represented as `lua_State*`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This value must be a thread; otherwise, the function returns `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If the value at the given index is a full userdata, returns its memory-block address.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] If the value is a light userdata, returns its value (a pointer).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns the type of the value in the given valid index, or `LUA_TNONE` for a non-valid but acceptable index.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The types returned by `lua_type` are coded by the following constants defined in `lua.h`: `LUA_TNIL`, `LUA_TNUMBER`, `LUA_TBOOLEAN`, `LUA_TSTRING`, `LUA_TTABLE`, `LUA_TFUNCTION`, `LUA_TUSERDATA`, `LUA_TTHREAD`, and `LUA_TLIGHTUSERDATA`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns the name of the type encoded by the value `tp`, which must be one the values returned by `lua_type`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns the pseudo-index that represents the `i`-th upvalue of the running function (see §4.2).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Returns the version number of this core.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The type of warning functions, called by Lua to emit warnings.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The first parameter is an opaque pointer set by `lua_setwarnf`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The second parameter is the warning message.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The third parameter is a boolean that indicates whether the message is to be continued by the message in the next call.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] See `warn` for more details about warnings.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] A message in a call with `tocont` true should be continued in another call to this function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The type of the writer function used by `lua_dump`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Every time `lua_dump` produces another piece of chunk, it calls the writer, passing along the buffer to be written (`p`), its size (`sz`), and the `ud` parameter supplied to `lua_dump`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The writer returns an error code: 0 means no errors; any other value means an error and stops `lua_dump` from calling the writer again.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Exchange values between different threads of the same state.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function pops `n` values from the stack `from`, and pushes them onto the stack `to`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function is equivalent to `lua_yieldk`, but it has no continuation (see §4.5).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Therefore, when the thread resumes, it continues the function that called the function calling `lua_yield`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] To avoid surprises, this function should be called only in a tail call.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] When a C function calls `lua_yieldk`, the running coroutine suspends its execution, and the call to `lua_resume` that started this coroutine returns.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] The parameter `nresults` is the number of values from the stack that will be passed as results to `lua_resume`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] When the coroutine is resumed again, Lua calls the given continuation function `k` to continue the execution of the C function that yielded (see §4.5).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This continuation function receives the same stack from the previous function, with the `n` results removed and replaced by the arguments passed to `lua_resume`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Moreover, the continuation function receives the value `ctx` that was passed to `lua_yieldk`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Usually, this function does not return; when the coroutine eventually resumes, it continues executing the continuation function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] However, there is one special case, which is when this function is called from inside a line or a count hook (see §4.7).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] In that case, `lua_yieldk` should be called with no continuation (probably in the form of `lua_yield`) and no results, and the hook should return immediately after the call.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Lua will yield and, when the coroutine resumes again, it will continue the normal execution of the (Lua) function that triggered the hook.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This function can raise an error if it is called from a thread with a pending C call with no continuation function (what is called a *C-call boundary*), or it is called from a thread that is not running inside a resume (typically the main thread).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Lua has no built-in debugging facilities.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] Instead, it offers a special interface by means of functions and *hooks*.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] This interface allows the construction of different kinds of debuggers, profilers, and other tools that need "inside information" from the interpreter.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] A structure used to carry different pieces of information about a function or an activation record.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] `lua_getstack` fills only the private part of this structure, for later use.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p03] To fill the other fields of `lua_Debug` with useful information, you must call `lua_getinfo` with an appropriate parameter.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The fields of `lua_Debug` have the following meaning: **`source`:** the source of the chunk that created the function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If `source` starts with a '`@`', it means that the function was defined in a file where the file name follows the '`@`'.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If `source` starts with a '`=`', the remainder of its contents describes the source in a user-dependent manner.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Otherwise, the function was defined in a string where `source` is that string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`srclen`:** The length of the string `source`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`short_src`:** a "printable" version of `source`, to be used in error messages.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`linedefined`:** the line number where the definition of the function starts.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`lastlinedefined`:** the line number where the definition of the function ends.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`what`:** the string `"Lua"` if the function is a Lua function, `"C"` if it is a C function, `"main"` if it is the main part of a chunk.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`currentline`:** the current line where the given function is executing.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] When no line information is available, `currentline` is set to -1.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`name`:** a reasonable name for the given function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Because functions in Lua are first-class values, they do not have a fixed name: some functions can be the value of multiple global variables, while others can be stored only in a table field.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The `lua_getinfo` function checks how the function was called to find a suitable name.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If it cannot find a name, then `name` is set to `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`namewhat`:** explains the `name` field.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The value of `namewhat` can be `"global"`, `"local"`, `"method"`, `"field"`, `"upvalue"`, or `""` (the empty string), according to how the function was called.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] (Lua uses the empty string when no other option seems to apply.) **`istailcall`:** true if this function invocation was called by a tail call.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] In this case, the caller of this level is not in the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`nups`:** the number of upvalues of the function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`nparams`:** the number of parameters of the function (always 0 for C functions).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`isvararg`:** true if the function is a variadic function (always true for C functions).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **`ftransfer`:** the index in the stack of the first value being "transferred", that is, parameters in a call or return values in a return.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] (The other values are in consecutive indices.) Using this index, you can access and modify these values through `lua_getlocal` and `lua_setlocal`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This field is only meaningful during a call hook, denoting the first parameter, or a return hook, denoting the first value being returned.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] (For call hooks, this value is always 1.) **`ntransfer`:** The number of values being transferred (see previous item).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Gets information about a specific function or function invocation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] To get information about a function invocation, the parameter `ar` must be a valid activation record that was filled by a previous call to `lua_getstack` or given as argument to a hook (see `lua_Hook`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] To get information about a function, you push it onto the stack and start the `what` string with the character '`>`'.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Each character in the string `what` selects some fields of the structure `ar` to be filled or a value to be pushed on the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] (Lines with no code include empty lines and comments.) If this option is given together with option '`f`', its table is pushed after the function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This is the only option that can raise a memory error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function returns 0 to signal an invalid option in `what`; even then the valid options are handled correctly.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Gets information about a local variable or a temporary value of a given activation record or a given function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] In the first case, the parameter `ar` must be a valid activation record that was filled by a previous call to `lua_getstack` or given as argument to a hook (see `lua_Hook`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The index `n` selects which local variable to inspect; see `debug.getlocal` for details about variable indices and names.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] `lua_getlocal` pushes the variable's value onto the stack and returns its name.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] In the second case, `ar` must be `NULL` and the function to be inspected must be on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] In this case, only parameters of Lua functions are visible (as there is no information about what variables are active) and no values are pushed onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns `NULL` (and pushes nothing) when the index is greater than the number of active local variables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Gets information about the interpreter runtime stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function fills parts of a `lua_Debug` structure with an identification of the *activation record* of the function executing at a given level.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Level 0 is the current running function, whereas level *n+1* is the function that has called level *n* (except for tail calls, which do not count in the stack).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] When called with a level greater than the stack depth, `lua_getstack` returns 0; otherwise it returns 1.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Gets information about the `n`-th upvalue of the closure at index `funcindex`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] It pushes the upvalue's value onto the stack and returns its name.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns `NULL` (and pushes nothing) when the index `n` is greater than the number of upvalues.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] See `debug.getupvalue` for more information about upvalues.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Whenever a hook is called, its `ar` argument has its field `event` set to the specific event that triggered the hook.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Lua identifies these events with the following constants: `LUA_HOOKCALL`, `LUA_HOOKRET`, `LUA_HOOKTAILCALL`, `LUA_HOOKLINE`, and `LUA_HOOKCOUNT`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Moreover, for line events, the field `currentline` is also set.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] To get the value of any other field in `ar`, the hook must call `lua_getinfo`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] For call events, `event` can be `LUA_HOOKCALL`, the normal value, or `LUA_HOOKTAILCALL`, for a tail call; in this case, there will be no corresponding return event.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] While Lua is running a hook, it disables other calls to hooks.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Therefore, if a hook calls back Lua to execute a function or a chunk, this execution occurs without any calls to hooks.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Hook functions cannot have continuations, that is, they cannot call `lua_yieldk`, `lua_pcallk`, or `lua_callk` with a non-null `k`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Hook functions can yield under the following conditions: Only count and line events can yield; to yield, a hook function must finish its execution calling `lua_yield` with `nresults` equal to zero (that is, with no values).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] `mask` specifies on which events the hook will be called: it is formed by a bitwise OR of the constants `LUA_MASKCALL`, `LUA_MASKRET`, `LUA_MASKLINE`, and `LUA_MASKCOUNT`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The `count` argument is only meaningful when the mask includes `LUA_MASKCOUNT`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] For each event, the hook is called as explained below: **The call hook:** is called when the interpreter calls a function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The hook is called just after Lua enters the new function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **The return hook:** is called when the interpreter returns from a function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The hook is called just before Lua leaves the function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **The line hook:** is called when the interpreter is about to start the execution of a new line of code, or when it jumps back in the code (even to the same line).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This event only happens while Lua is executing a Lua function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] **The count hook:** is called after the interpreter executes every `count` instructions.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Hooks are disabled by setting `mask` to zero.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Sets the value of a local variable of a given activation record.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] It assigns the value on the top of the stack to the variable and returns its name.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns `NULL` (and pops nothing) when the index is greater than the number of active local variables.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Parameters `ar` and `n` are as in the function `lua_getlocal`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] It assigns the value on the top of the stack to the upvalue and returns its name.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns `NULL` (and pops nothing) when the index `n` is greater than the number of upvalues.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Parameters `funcindex` and `n` are as in the function `lua_getupvalue`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns a unique identifier for the upvalue numbered `n` from the closure at index `funcindex`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] These unique identifiers allow a program to check whether different closures share upvalues.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Lua closures that share an upvalue (that is, that access a same external local variable) will return identical ids for those upvalue indices.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Parameters `funcindex` and `n` are as in the function `lua_getupvalue`, but `n` cannot be greater than the number of upvalues.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Make the `n1`-th upvalue of the Lua closure at index `funcindex1` refer to the `n2`-th upvalue of the Lua closure at index `funcindex2`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The *auxiliary library* provides several convenient functions to interface C with Lua.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] While the basic API provides the primitive functions for all interactions between C and Lua, the auxiliary library provides higher-level functions for some common tasks.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] All functions and types from the auxiliary library are defined in header file `lauxlib.h` and have a prefix `luaL_`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] All functions in the auxiliary library are built on top of the basic API, and so they provide nothing that cannot be done with that API.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Nevertheless, the use of the auxiliary library ensures more consistency to your code.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Several functions in the auxiliary library use internally some extra stack slots.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] When a function in the auxiliary library uses less than five slots, it does not check the stack size; it simply assumes that there are enough slots.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Several functions in the auxiliary library are used to check C function arguments.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Because the error message is formatted for arguments (e.g., "`bad argument #1`"), you should not use these functions for other stack values.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Functions called `luaL_check*` always raise an error if the check is not satisfied.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Here we list all functions and types from the auxiliary library in alphabetical order.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Adds the byte `c` to the buffer `B` (see `luaL_Buffer`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Adds a copy of the string `s` to the buffer `B` (see `luaL_Buffer`), replacing any occurrence of the string `p` with the string `r`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Adds the string pointed to by `s` with length `l` to the buffer `B` (see `luaL_Buffer`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Adds to the buffer `B` a string of length `n` previously copied to the buffer area (see `luaL_prepbuffer`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Adds the zero-terminated string pointed to by `s` to the buffer `B` (see `luaL_Buffer`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Adds the value on the top of the stack to the buffer `B` (see `luaL_Buffer`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This is the only function on string buffers that can (and must) be called with an extra element on the stack, which is the value to be added to the buffer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If it is not, raises an error with a standard message (see `luaL_argerror`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If it is not, raises an error about the type of the argument `arg` with a standard message (see `luaL_typeerror`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] A string buffer allows C code to build Lua strings piecemeal.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Its pattern of use is as follows: First declare a variable `b` of type `luaL_Buffer`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Then initialize it with a call `luaL_buffinit(L, &b)`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Then add string pieces to the buffer calling any of the `luaL_add*` functions.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Finish by calling `luaL_pushresult(&b)`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This call leaves the final string on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If you know beforehand the maximum size of the resulting string, you can use the buffer like this: First declare a variable `b` of type `luaL_Buffer`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Then initialize it and preallocate a space of size `sz` with a call `luaL_buffinitsize(L, &b, sz)`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Then produce the string into that space.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Finish by calling `luaL_pushresultsize(&b, sz)`, where `sz` is the total size of the resulting string copied into that space (which may be less than or equal to the preallocated size).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] During its normal operation, a string buffer uses a variable number of stack slots.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] So, while using a buffer, you cannot assume that you know where the top of the stack is.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] You can use the stack between successive calls to buffer operations as long as that use is balanced; that is, when you call a buffer operation, the stack is at the same level it was immediately after the previous buffer operation.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] (The only exception to this rule is `luaL_addvalue`.) After calling `luaL_pushresult`, the stack is back to its level when the buffer was initialized, plus the final string on its top.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns the address of the current content of buffer `B` (see `luaL_Buffer`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Note that any addition to the buffer may invalidate this address.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Initializes a buffer `B` (see `luaL_Buffer`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function does not allocate any space; the buffer must be declared as a variable.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns the length of the current content of buffer `B` (see `luaL_Buffer`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Equivalent to the sequence `luaL_buffinit`, `luaL_prepbuffsize`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Removes `n` bytes from the buffer `B` (see `luaL_Buffer`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The buffer must have at least that many bytes.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If the object at index `obj` has a metatable and this metatable has a field `e`, this function calls this field passing the object as its only argument.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] In this case this function returns true and pushes onto the stack the value returned by the call.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If there is no metatable or no metamethod, this function returns false without pushing any value on the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Checks whether the function has an argument of any type (including **nil**) at position `arg`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Checks whether the function argument `arg` is an integer (or can be converted to an integer) and returns this integer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Checks whether the function argument `arg` is a string and returns this string; if `l` is not `NULL` fills its referent with the string's length.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function uses `lua_tolstring` to get its result, so all conversions and caveats of that function apply here.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Checks whether the function argument `arg` is a number and returns this number converted to a `lua_Number`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Checks whether the function argument `arg` is a string and searches for this string in the array `lst` (which must be NULL-terminated).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns the index in the array where the string was found.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Raises an error if the argument is not a string or if the string cannot be found.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If `def` is not `NULL`, the function uses `def` as a default value when there is no argument `arg` or when this argument is **nil**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This is a useful function for mapping strings to C enums.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Grows the stack size to `top + sz` elements, raising an error if the stack cannot grow to that size.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] `msg` is an additional text to go into the error message (or `NULL` for no additional text).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Checks whether the function argument `arg` is a string and returns this string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Checks whether the function argument `arg` has type `t`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] See `lua_type` for the encoding of types for `t`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Checks whether the function argument `arg` is a userdata of the type `tname` (see `luaL_newmetatable`) and returns the userdata's memory-block address (see `lua_touserdata`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Checks whether the code making the call and the Lua library being called are using the same version of Lua and the same numeric types.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] It returns 0 (`LUA_OK`) if there are no errors, or 1 in case of errors.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The error message format is given by `fmt` plus any extra arguments, following the same rules of `lua_pushfstring`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] It also adds at the beginning of the message the file name and the line number where the error occurred, if this information is available.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function never returns, but it is an idiom to use it in C functions as `return luaL_error(*args*)`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function produces the return values for process-related functions in the standard library (`os.execute` and `io.close`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function produces the return values for file-related functions in the standard library (`io.open`, `os.rename`, `file:seek`, etc.).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Pushes onto the stack the field `e` from the metatable of the object at index `obj` and returns the type of the pushed value.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If the object does not have a metatable, or if the metatable does not have this field, pushes nothing and returns `LUA_TNIL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Pushes onto the stack the metatable associated with the name `tname` in the registry (see `luaL_newmetatable`), or **nil** if there is no metatable associated with that name.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Ensures that the value `t[fname]`, where `t` is the value at index `idx`, is a table, and pushes that table onto the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns true if it finds a previous table there and false if it creates a new table.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Creates a copy of string `s`, replacing any occurrence of the string `p` with the string `r`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Pushes the resulting string on the stack and returns it.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns the "length" of the value at the given index as a number; it is equivalent to the '`#`' operator in Lua (see §3.4.7).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Raises an error if the result of the operation is not an integer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Equivalent to `luaL_loadbufferx` with `mode` equal to `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function uses `lua_load` to load the chunk in the buffer pointed to by `buff` with size `sz`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function returns the same results as `lua_load`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] `name` is the chunk name, used for debug information and error messages.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The string `mode` works as in the function `lua_load`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Equivalent to `luaL_loadfilex` with `mode` equal to `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function uses `lua_load` to load the chunk in the file named `filename`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If `filename` is `NULL`, then it loads from the standard input.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The first line in the file is ignored if it starts with a `#`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function returns the same results as `lua_load` or `LUA_ERRFILE` for file-related errors.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] As `lua_load`, this function only loads the chunk; it does not run it.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This function uses `lua_load` to load the chunk in the zero-terminated string `s`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Also as `lua_load`, this function only loads the chunk; it does not run it.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Creates a new table and registers there the functions in the list `l`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The array `l` must be the actual array, not a pointer to it.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Creates a new table with a size optimized to store all entries in the array `l` (but does not actually store them).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] It is intended to be used in conjunction with `luaL_setfuncs` (see `luaL_newlib`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If the registry already has the key `tname`, returns 0.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Otherwise, creates a new table to be used as a metatable for userdata, adds to this new table the pair `__name = tname`, adds to the registry the pair `[tname] = new table`, and returns 1.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] In both cases, the function pushes onto the stack the final value associated with `tname` in the registry.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] It calls `lua_newstate` with an allocator based on the ISO C allocation functions and then sets a warning function and a panic function (see §4.4) that print messages to the standard error output.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns the new state, or `NULL` if there is a memory allocation error.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Opens all standard Lua libraries into the given state.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] This macro is defined as follows: (lua_isnoneornil(L,(arg)) ?
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] In words, if the argument `arg` is nil or absent, the macro results in the default `dflt`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Otherwise, it results in the result of calling `func` with the state `L` and the argument index `arg` as arguments.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Note that it evaluates the expression `dflt` only if needed.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If the function argument `arg` is an integer (or it is convertible to an integer), returns this integer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If this argument is absent or is **nil**, returns `d`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If the function argument `arg` is a string, returns this string.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If `l` is not `NULL`, fills its referent with the result's length.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If the result is `NULL` (only possible when returning `d` and `d == NULL`), its length is considered zero.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If the function argument `arg` is a number, returns this number as a `lua_Number`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Equivalent to `luaL_prepbuffsize` with the predefined size `LUAL_BUFFERSIZE`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Returns an address to a space of size `sz` where you can copy a string to be added to buffer `B` (see `luaL_Buffer`).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] After copying the string into this space you must call `luaL_addsize` with the size of the string to actually add it to the buffer.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Pushes the **fail** value onto the stack (see §6).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Finishes the use of buffer `B` leaving the final string on the top of the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Equivalent to the sequence `luaL_addsize`, `luaL_pushresult`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Creates and returns a *reference*, in the table at index `t`, for the object on the top of the stack (and pops the object).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] As long as you do not manually add integer keys into the table `t`, `luaL_ref` ensures the uniqueness of the key it returns.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] You can retrieve an object referred by the reference `r` by calling `lua_rawgeti(L, t, r)`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The function `luaL_unref` frees a reference.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If the object on the top of the stack is **nil**, `luaL_ref` returns the constant `LUA_REFNIL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] The constant `LUA_NOREF` is guaranteed to be different from any reference returned by `luaL_ref`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Type for arrays of functions to be registered by `luaL_setfuncs`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] `name` is the function name and `func` is a pointer to the function.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Any array of `luaL_Reg` must end with a sentinel entry in which both `name` and `func` are `NULL`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If `package.loaded[modname]` is not true, calls the function `openf` with the string `modname` as an argument and sets the call result to `package.loaded[modname]`, as if that function has been called through `require`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] If `glb` is true, also stores the module into the global `modname`.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Leaves a copy of the module on the stack.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Registers all functions in the array `l` (see `luaL_Reg`) into the table on the top of the stack (below optional upvalues, see next).
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] When `nup` is not zero, all functions are created with `nup` upvalues, initialized with copies of the `nup` values previously pushed on the stack on top of the library table.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] These values are popped from the stack after the registration.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] A function with a `NULL` value represents a placeholder, which is filled with **false**.
[src:lua/5-4-manual-p04] Sets the metatable of the object on the top of the stack as the metatable associated with name `tname` in the registry (see `luaL_newmetatable`).
